  "key_historical_facts": {
    "kentucky_brothers_tradition": "Book records family tradition (p. iii, Appendix II p. 230) that Henry I's brothers Leonard, William, and Luke left Leonardtown, Md., for Kentucky ~1791. Charles Mattingly (1803-1897) testified Henry I was 'very much hurt' by this. Charles named William as the brother he remembered. This is the closest the book comes to Hunter's Kentucky Mattingly line.",
    "hardin_creek_kentucky_line": "Appendix II (Hoye, p. 230): 'The Kentucky Mattinglys trace their ancestry to Charles, whose sons, William, Leonard and Luke, settled in Hardin Creek, Kentucky, in 1786.' This may be a different Charles than the book's Samuel Mattingly's son Charles (b. 1803). The 1786 date predates Henry I's brothers going to KY in 1791.",
    "early_colonial_MD": "Thomas Mattingly I died before July 24, 1664 (Appendix III). Wife Elizabeth filed executor's bond that day. Family (Thomas, Elizabeth, Thomas II, Cezar, Elizabeth) arrived Maryland 'prior to 1665' per Hoye. On rent rolls 1663. This is the earliest confirmed Mattingly in Maryland.",
    "henry_i_birth_correction": "Post-publication letter (July 8, 1969) from Our Lady of Mt. Carmel, Buckeye Lake OH: Henry I born July 3, 1751 (not 'about 1750' as in book). His father was John Mattingly (~1720) and Elizabeth Mattingly; Henry I was their sixth child; oldest child born 1741.",
    "mattingly_settlement_ohio": "Founded by William Mattingly (No.40) who arrived spring 1812, Muskingum County, Ohio (near Zanesville). St. Mary's Church built 1856. Became center of Ohio Catholic Mattingly families.",
    "blooming_rose_md": "A Catholic settlement in what became Garrett County, Md. James Mattingly (No.15) and his brother John Jr. lived there 1820s-1831.",
    "barnet_joseph_richard_mattingly": "These three plus Henry I took the Oath of Fidelity to the Revolution March 2, 1778, Washington Co., Md. Charles Hoye says they were 'presumably sons of Luke Mattingly who resided near Hagerstown, Md.' (p. iii, v; Appendix II p. 230)"
  }
